The ‘bee car’ that prevents collisions
To advance in the development of technologies for accident prevention Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, in particular, by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flight of bees, prevents accidents.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step in collision prevention technologies.
The engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Chief Public Relations Officer for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C presents itself as an extension of Nissan’s four-area Safety Shield.
This robot intends to strengthen the collision prevention capability of the brand’s vehicles.
During their flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that looks very similar to Nissan’s Safety Shield.
But most importantly, the composite eyes of the bee, capable of seeing at an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, allowing it to fly uninterruptedly within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers designed what they have called a laser range finder.
It detects obstacles located up to two meters away within a radius of 180 degrees in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance to said object and sends a signal to an onboard microprocessor which immediately translates into collision prevention.
“At the moment he detects an obstacle, the small robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by rotating its wheels at a straight or larger angle to avoid collision.
The biggest difference with any existing system is that the maneuver of evasion is totally instinctive.
Otherwise, the robot would not be able to react fast enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and lead engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be diverted up or down, or diagonally; it can only be moved in two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to rotate its wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and slowdown, to help the small robot avoid collisions.
“This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act according to that data.
It does not need to save information or intuitive logic from previous manoeuvres, so it can work continuously with just a couple dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise you, but we’re not talking about gigas of memory, not even megas.”
This is the first step towards developing new collision prevention technologies, a technology that Nissan predicts will be introduced into standard cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the variety of lithium ions.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a satellite navigation GPS system to guide the driver to its destination while avoiding obstacles on the road.
