Rafael Correa in Quito this Monday.
Refounding the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, on the example of his colleagues and friends, it is the third to put a draft for a new Constitution for the vote.
Mission completed as 64% of voters voted “yes” to the referendum, according to official results that referred to 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" obtained 28%, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were blank votes.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half of the suffrage plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exit of electoral centers and a count by a non-governmental organization had announced a broad "yes" victory, estimating it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa also claimed the victory of his draft Constitution on Sunday night.
The " Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly," he had assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians leading the government of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
Thus, Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also by his Chilean colleague Micaela Bachelet.
The elections, which will take place in full calmness, according to the observer mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), referred to a text of 444 points that consolidated the " new socialism " defended by the president.
The draft Constitution involves increasing the power of the State over the economy, reserving it the " development planning " of a country that lives essentially thanks to the extraction of oil by foreign companies and thanks to currencies that send their emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants reinforced powers to the Head of State, who will be able to do up to two consecutive four-year terms each and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa already announced that he would use this power and want a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of the freeness of health and education services that the president began to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, in which 50% of the population lives under the poverty threshold.
It finally foresees the prohibition of the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington to use an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American anti-drug operations.
19 kidnapped people released in Chad
An Egyptian command launched the assault on the abductors of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts kidnapped ten days ago in the desert arrived unharmed in the Egyptian capital after being released Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by the Egyptian special forces in Chad.
They all looked good upon arrival at 3:30 aboard a special aircraft at the military base of Al Maza, adjacent to the international airport of Cairo.
Helicopters immediately transported them to the Maadi hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, for medical testing, so they were unable to talk to the press.
"They are well in health" and "no ransom was paid" to the kidnappers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garana said at the airport.
On September 19, these hostages fell in the possession of 35 unknown kidnappers while enjoying an off-road safari in a desert area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, in the confines of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and since then they have moved from one zulo to another.
The group consisted of eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the travel agency Aegyptous, in charge of the safari organization.
An Egyptian security official said 30 special forces members, carried aboard two helicopters, had launched the assault overnight before dawn.
"A shooting exchange occurred, and they killed half of the kidnappers, the others have fled," said the official who kept the anonymous one.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "lightning" unit were sent to Sudan, where they were supported by German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned in Belgrade the role played by the secret agents and members of the Italian special forces.
"We have to recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and the effectiveness of our men of the intelligence services, of the special forces," he said.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
On the eve of the day, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol an all-terrain vehicle on board which were the kidnappers, who killed six, including the Chadian chief and arrested two.
He also stated that they were related to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan-Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), a statement immediately denied by this group.
Letters - Silent Most of Culture
A debate on the financing of culture is headlined and occupies the current election campaign.
Better that way.
But a sector of our cultural life is always forgotten.
Who will stand up to denounce the miserable sums awarded to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historical sites that are starving?
Which politician will dare to remind the federal government of neglecting its monuments and heritage buildings?
Why do we not have true laws that effectively preserve our heritage as in Canada and Quebec?
Did you know that the French government spends three and a half million euros to restore only the castle of Chinon in the Loire Valley?
In the United States, it is written in its Constitution that the protection of heritage is part of the culture of Americans and that this heritage has to be protected by all citizens, all elected and all government departments, and all this, in concertation.
In Quebec, in the Federation of Societies of History of Quebec, at least 40,000 benevolent people regrouped into 211 societies of history, heritage, archives and genealogy are concerned to search history, preserve with little money lots of private archives and preserve archaeological vestiges.
These are often the guardian dogs of our heritage, who protest with energy and despair when promoters and responsible throw their bulldozers against our old stones and our forgotten cemeteries.
For when, a monument to history and heritage?
The governments of the Netherlands nationalize a portion of Fortis Bank.
The states of the Netherlands - being the first in Europe - will help with a nationalization of the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis that is in trouble due to the effect of the mortgage crisis of the North American market: the three countries will support a total of €11.2 billion to this financial and insurance institution that also has business in Hungary.
This weekend the Belgian, Luxembourg and Netherlands governments held consultations at the highest level with the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commission’s responsible for economic competition.
The Fortis Bank is the first to suffer the eurozone crisis in the context of the international financial crisis that has occurred in several waves more than a year ago, therefore the decisions taken with respect to the Bank, in a sense can be considered as precedent.
According to the decision taken early Sunday morning, the three states will buy approximately half (49 percent) of the Bank’s property in their area.
The Bank will certainly sell a portion of its business, including mostly the activities - mainly insurance - purchased last year from the Dutch ABN Amró.
Fortis shares began a sharp decline last week and by the second half of the week there were already significant signs of crisis in the institution.
However, analysts agree to note that with its 85,000 employees, this Bank is too large to allow it to break down.
The company’s shares decreased by 12 percent on Friday alone, which is the lowest point in the last 14 years.
Since January, the stock value has declined by more than two-thirds.
Looking at the current stock prices, the total value of the group’s capital in the market is around 14 billion euros, but according to the company’s executives this is not real.
The Bank’s management attributed the sharp drop in Fortis’ shares to the insecurities of the U.S. market in connection with the approval of the $700 billion U.S. package plan.
On Monday, the stocks showed a slight increase.
On Friday, they appointed Filip Dierckx as the bank’s new chief executive officer.
The Bank also sought private investors, but so far no one has given a concrete offer.
The Belgian government had previously assured that investors didn’t have to worry, they wouldn’t lose their money.
So far there was no panic among the Bank’s clients, they did not invade the banking offices to withdraw their money.
Fortis has its own branch in Hungary and has also purchased leasing companies.
Fox in the chickenhouse
In the United States, health and life insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract when viewing the medication purchase data.
The privacy policy specialists fear that the market for personal data will become uncontrollable.
"There are programs for the protection of personal data, which in all cases links the use of prescription data to the approval of the given person.
The same should be in independent hands, because otherwise, "we trust the chickenstall to the fox" - the Washington Post quotes Richard Dick, designer of the prescription tracking program.
Insurance companies depend on the price of insurance and the amount of compensation for the customer’s health status and if they believe the risk is excessive, they simply don’t make the contract.
Before, they sent the client to medical control and signed the contract with him already knowing the outcome of the control.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: with the customer identification number he easily gets from pharmacies the list of drugs purchased in the last year and a half and the program itself draws the conclusion about the illnesses and the health status of the customer.
For example, if you systematically take large doses of cholesterol-lowering pills, it indicates that your blood fat level is virtually incurably high, so you are immediately included in a higher risk category.
They circulate numerous versions of the program, some even set a number of risk, so the insurance company in addition to the management has barely anything to do, although there are small difficulties in this regard.
Among the disadvantages of the program is for example that some medicines are multi-purpose, for example certain substances serve both to treat headache and heat waves and even as antidepressants.
The latter is an important risk increase factor for insurance companies while the first ones do not.
Special companies were established to consult and process these data, which before acquiring the necessary information from the pharmacies, request the patient’s approval.
Authorities have already forced them to do this, although they have not been fined for the negligence so far.
Some companies are also lately preparing the results of the laboratory tests and combining them with drug consumption data obtain more accurate information about the patient’s health status.
More and more companies have access to this data and simultaneously it is increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is an exclusive law for the protection of personal health data, but it applies only to insurance companies and those providing health services.
The bill that gives the authority for the control of specialized companies for the provision of personal data is already before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is insufficient: therefore he developed his program, which will require the specific approval of the person for the provision of his own personal data.
It is another issue that such a person cannot deny his approval, because otherwise the insurance companies will not sign the contract with him.
So the chickens, despite everything, are exposed to the goodwill of the fox.
