Although the European Union recognizes that India is a great democratic power in development that should have more voice and vote in international affairs, the member countries have not yet been able to reach a common denominator on whether to support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This issue has not been addressed at the ninth summit launched yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, EU turn president, José Manuel Barroso, Commission president, and Javier Solana, chief foreign policy representative, welcomed Manmohan Singh, India’s Prime Minister with whom they reached an agreement to double their trade exchange to more than one hundred billion euros in five years.
Given that between 2000 and 2007 the trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an excessively ambitious goal.
This has legally harmonised the twenty-six bilateral civil aviation agreements with India, so air transport will also be able to fly in the future.
India will sign the free trade treaty with the Union until the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to accelerate negotiations.
The goal is balance, because while the EU is India’s first trading partner, New Delhi only ranks ninth among the Union’s trading partners.
